ndy, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Is-sur-Tille, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Is-sur-Tille, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France","Westmill, Hertfordshire, England":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richardson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Richard   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Ritson  .","Americanized form (and a Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Richardsson</b> or <b>Rikardsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  , <i>Rikard</i>.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Richardsen</b> or Norwegian <b>Rikardsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Richarson","meanings":["English: variant of   Richardson  ."]},{"name":"Richerson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson   or perhaps a patronymic from   Richer  ."]},{"name":"Richard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Richeson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson  , but compare   Richerson  ."]},{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Richardson was born in 1480, in Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph Richardson, was 25 and his mother, Jeanne Michiell, was 18. He married Katherine Duxford about January 1495. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1540, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1480–1540":"1480–1540","1475–1550":"1475–1550","1503–1563":"1503–1563","1506–1562":"1506–1562","1512–1540":"1512–1540","1455–1520":"1455–1520","1462–1503":"1462–1503","Abt. Jan 1495":"umbes jaanuar 1495","1462":"1462","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","1503":"1503","1512":"1512","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1563":"1563","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1562":"1562","1506":"1506","Westmill, Hertfordshire, , England":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa,